Like ghosts or spirits or devils?

4
00:03:50,313 --> 00:03:51,815
Those are examples.

5
00:03:51,982 --> 00:03:55,202
Actions or events
which we cannot explain through science.

6
00:03:55,360 --> 00:03:56,361
Good.

7
00:03:56,528 --> 00:03:58,729
Before the discovery
of a pathogenic theory of medicine,

8
00:03:58,739 --> 00:04:01,492
people believed that
sickness was caused by evil spirits.

9
00:04:02,909 --> 00:04:04,627
A show of hands, if you get sick,

10
00:04:04,703 --> 00:04:06,705
who here would
rather see a priest before a doctor?

11
00:04:08,457 --> 00:04:10,459
Who here believes in God?

12
00:04:11,668 --> 00:04:13,386
Heaven? Hell?

13
00:04:14,212 --> 00:04:15,555
The apocalypse?

14
00:04:16,715 --> 00:04:17,716
Ghosts?

15
00:04:19,509 --> 00:04:22,012
Really? No one here believes in ghosts.
Interesting.

16
00:04:24,806 --> 00:04:27,355
David Q., one of my first patients,

17
00:04:27,517 --> 00:04:30,691
was a perfectly normal 12-year-old boy.

18
00:04:31,188 --> 00:04:33,316
One day, that all changed.

19
00:04:33,523 --> 00:04:35,196
<i>Who are you drawing, David?</i>

20
00:04:38,361 --> 00:04:39,453
<i>You know.</i>

21
00:04:40,155 --> 00:04:42,829
<i>Tell me again, to the camera.</i>

22
00:04:46,119 --> 00:04:47,462
<i>Mr. Gregor,</i>

23
00:04:49,372 --> 00:04:51,841
<i>the man that makes things happen.</i>

24
00:05:08,725 --> 00:05:11,399
What if you could prove
that the supernatural was merely

25
00:05:11,561 --> 00:05:15,407
a manifestation of what already
exists in the mind, the subconscious?

26
00:05:15,565 --> 00:05:17,567
- What you're doing is immoral.
- Traitor.

27
00:05:17,692 --> 00:05:19,160
That was disgusting. How dare you do that?

28
00:05:19,319 --> 00:05:20,640
- It's not disgusting!
- You left!

29
00:05:20,654 --> 00:05:23,533
No, don't take it personally.
Don't take it personally.

30
00:05:24,324 --> 00:05:27,168
The onus is on the scientist
to prove himself.

31
00:05:27,577 --> 00:05:31,207
So, where to start? With the individual.

32
00:05:32,833 --> 00:05:36,258
You cure one patient, you cure all mankind.

33
00:05:38,255 --> 00:05:40,678
- You have no idea.
- You don't get to have an opinion.

34
00:05:40,757 --> 00:05:42,430
- You don't know how crazy...
- It's so bizarre.

35
00:05:42,551 --> 00:05:45,680
Harry, will you take that for me? And this?

36
00:05:46,763 --> 00:05:49,437
Phillip, you're welcome back anytime.

37
00:05:50,600 --> 00:05:52,853
Let's have a chat.
I'll see you guys back at the house.

38
00:05:56,773 --> 00:06:00,448
<i>There's not much of a budget,
everyone's working for science.</i>

39
00:06:01,403 --> 00:06:05,283
Your job would be
to document every step of the experiment.

40
00:06:06,449 --> 00:06:08,201
I hope you don't scare easily.

41
00:06:11,288 --> 00:06:12,460
Do you speak?

42
00:06:13,206 --> 00:06:14,458
Of course.

43
00:06:14,875 --> 00:06:16,969
Tell me about yourself, Brian.

44
00:06:17,794 --> 00:06:19,467
There's not much to tell.

45
00:06:21,131 --> 00:06:24,305
I like cameras, that's my nature, I guess.

46
00:06:24,593 --> 00:06:25,936
To be curious?

47
00:06:26,303 --> 00:06:27,395
To film.

48
00:06:28,471 --> 00:06:31,475
- And what's your passion?
- Passion?

49
00:06:31,808 --> 00:06:35,984
Yes, what story are you looking for
with that camera of yours?

50
00:06:36,229 --> 00:06:38,231
I don't know, everything.

51
00:06:40,650 --> 00:06:42,152
Are you a believer?

52
00:06:46,323 --> 00:06:48,166
My mother's religious.

53
00:06:49,159 --> 00:06:51,332
My father's a banker, a clerk.

54
00:06:52,454 --> 00:06:54,798
My father works in town,
my mother is at home.

55
00:06:58,460 --> 00:06:59,461
I wonder,

56
00:07:00,170 --> 00:07:04,346
are you avoiding my question
out of a reluctance to talk about yourself,

57
00:07:04,841 --> 00:07:06,843
or because you're genuinely confused?

58
00:07:09,763 --> 00:07:14,189
I suppose I don't know what I believe in yet.

59
00:07:15,310 --> 00:07:16,778
Well, that's fair enough.

60
00:07:17,270 --> 00:07:18,362
Well, Brian,

61
00:07:20,273 --> 00:07:24,278
welcome to the experiment.
You are our official chronicler.

62
00:07:34,955 --> 00:07:39,335
I work with the A.V.,
the audiovisual department.

63
00:07:39,501 --> 00:07:41,219
But you are a student here, no?

64
00:07:41,670 --> 00:07:44,344
No, I'd never get in here.

65
00:07:44,631 --> 00:07:46,975
<i>So</i> how did you
get involved with the Experiment?

66
00:07:47,133 --> 00:07:50,478
I volunteered as a subject.

67
00:07:52,055 --> 00:07:55,059
Professor Coupland, or Joseph if you like,

68
00:07:55,225 --> 00:07:56,977
he thought I was all wrong.

69
00:07:57,894 --> 00:08:00,317
Not tortured enough, apparently.

70
00:08:01,231 --> 00:08:04,826
He already had someone truly psychotic.

71
00:08:09,656 --> 00:08:10,999
<i>I see someone.</i>

72
00:08:12,242 --> 00:08:14,586
<i>Good, Jane. Who do you see?</i>

73
00:08:15,537 --> 00:08:17,539
<i>Do you recognize this person?</i>

74
00:08:18,540 --> 00:08:21,760
<i>I don't know. I'm not sure.</i>

75
00:08:22,836 --> 00:08:26,340
<i>A girl... I see a little girl.</i>

76
00:08:30,427 --> 00:08:31,428
<i>No,</i>

77
00:08:35,098 --> 00:08:36,441
<i>maybe a doll.</i>

78
00:08:44,941 --> 00:08:46,284
<i>Something's wrong.</i>

79
00:08:47,110 --> 00:08:50,785
<i>It's okay, you're perfectly safe.</i>

80
00:08:52,115 --> 00:08:54,209
<i>Her name is Evey. I don't like her.</i>

81
00:08:57,287 --> 00:08:59,585
<i>The doll's name is Evey?</i>

82
00:09:04,377 --> 00:09:05,799
<i>I just need to sleep.</i>

83
00:09:10,133 --> 00:09:13,979
Be quiet! Calm down!
It's just the pipes, it's just the pipes!

84
00:09:20,060 --> 00:09:21,152
Crazy fun, no?

85
00:09:23,646 --> 00:09:24,647
Go on up.

86
00:09:48,171 --> 00:09:49,514
It's for her own protection.

87
00:09:50,840 --> 00:09:52,012
And ours.

88
00:09:56,304 --> 00:09:57,647
What's wrong with her?

89
00:09:57,847 --> 00:10:01,021
Suicidal.
She remembers nothing from her past.

90
00:10:02,018 --> 00:10:05,864
Foster child, abandoned.
Passed from house to house.

91
00:10:08,108 --> 00:10:10,611
Families would keep her for a bit, then,

92
00:10:11,653 --> 00:10:15,123
you know, things would happen.

93
00:10:15,990 --> 00:10:19,369
The furniture would move,
objects would catch on fire.

94
00:10:19,744 --> 00:10:22,213
The authorities were
convinced she was possessed.

95
00:10:23,123 --> 00:10:25,967
Luckily, Joseph discovered her.

96
00:10:26,376 --> 00:10:28,845
He ruled out schizophrenia, the usual.

97
00:10:29,879 --> 00:10:31,677
Then he measured her brain waves.

98
00:10:32,173 --> 00:10:34,551
Frequencies off the charts, look.

99
00:10:36,052 --> 00:10:39,056
That's why he chose her.
He took her from the asylum.

100
00:10:43,977 --> 00:10:47,732
Well, Brian, welcome to the Experiment.

101
00:10:54,070 --> 00:10:58,075
Don't look into her eyes,
don't say anything to her if you can help it.

102
00:10:58,533 --> 00:11:01,582
I can't have the experiment
corrupted by outside inﬂuences.

103
00:11:02,203 --> 00:11:03,420
I understand.

104
00:11:32,775 --> 00:11:33,776
What?

105
00:11:34,569 --> 00:11:36,412
Did you think
my head was going to spin off?

106
00:11:42,577 --> 00:11:45,296
Sorry if I disturbed you.

107
00:11:47,207 --> 00:11:49,630
- It comes and goes.
- Excuse me?

108
00:11:49,751 --> 00:11:51,344
What's inside.

109
00:11:53,421 --> 00:11:57,051
- Stop staring at my wrists.
- Sorry.

110
00:11:57,884 --> 00:12:00,307
I promised Joseph that I wouldn't try again,

111
00:12:02,722 --> 00:12:04,315
that I'd give him time.

112
00:12:07,477 --> 00:12:08,649
Is there time?

113
00:12:10,730 --> 00:12:13,153
Yeah, of course.

114
00:12:13,900 --> 00:12:15,322
Can he cure me?

115
00:12:16,778 --> 00:12:18,280
I'm sure he can.

116
00:12:21,324 --> 00:12:23,076
I just want to get better.

117
00:12:27,580 --> 00:12:29,582
Tell Joseph that I'm ready.

118
00:12:31,668 --> 00:12:36,014
Ask him to let me sleep. I'm begging you.

119
00:12:39,842 --> 00:12:41,014
And, Brian,

120
00:12:45,014 --> 00:12:46,516
thank you.

121
00:13:00,571 --> 00:13:01,572
Seen a ghost?

122
00:13:03,741 --> 00:13:05,664
She knew my name.

123
00:13:05,827 --> 00:13:08,546
She probably heard us talking about you
at some point.

124
00:13:09,163 --> 00:13:10,380
She's no fool.

125
00:13:12,208 --> 00:13:14,427
She said to tell you

126
00:13:15,503 --> 00:13:18,723
that she needs sleep and that she's ready.

127
00:13:18,881 --> 00:13:22,306
Excellent, that is a good sign.

128
00:13:23,219 --> 00:13:25,642
I really don't know if I can do this, sir.

129
00:13:25,722 --> 00:13:30,478
If you think you're scared,
imagine how she feels?

130
00:13:31,894 --> 00:13:35,899
Besides, aren't you just a little bit intrigued?

131
00:13:38,609 --> 00:13:40,657
Hey, you! You over there!

132
00:13:40,737 --> 00:13:43,832
Is he in? Is he in that house?

133
00:13:44,240 --> 00:13:48,586
I am going to go mad
if this sound does not stop!

134
00:13:49,078 --> 00:13:51,547
What's the point, exactly?

135
00:13:51,873 --> 00:13:55,252
Remember,
"Cure one patient, we cure mankind"?

136
00:13:55,877 --> 00:13:58,426
Jane Harper is that patient.

137
00:13:58,921 --> 00:14:01,845
If we can push our subject
to manifest negative energy

138
00:14:01,924 --> 00:14:03,926
in the form of telekinetic activity,

139
00:14:05,261 --> 00:14:10,062
we can harvest that energy and remove it,
like extracting a tumor.

140
00:14:11,017 --> 00:14:13,691
We cure mental illness for good.

141
00:14:16,773 --> 00:14:18,116
Are you a skeptic, Brian?

142
00:14:18,775 --> 00:14:19,776
Pardon?

143
00:14:20,610 --> 00:14:22,453
Don't you think we can cure Harper?

144
00:14:25,114 --> 00:14:29,620
We can't have non-believers
in this house, Brian.

145
00:14:30,703 --> 00:14:32,797
It's a destructive energy

146
00:14:34,123 --> 00:14:36,296
in a constructive space.

147
00:14:41,547 --> 00:14:42,799
Not again.

148
00:14:43,174 --> 00:14:45,643
Harry, will you turn the music off upstairs?

149
00:14:46,469 --> 00:14:48,813
Well, thank you and good luck. I'm sorry.

150
00:14:48,930 --> 00:14:51,934
It won't happen again.

151
00:14:53,810 --> 00:14:54,982
You just clap.

152
00:15:01,943 --> 00:15:05,072
Hello, Jane.
We've brought something for you.

153
00:15:07,073 --> 00:15:11,499
You can put all your bad thoughts and
negative energy into the doll, Jane.

154
00:15:11,661 --> 00:15:14,460
Get rid of them, get rid of them for good.

155
00:15:15,415 --> 00:15:17,258
Evey doesn't look like this.

156
00:15:19,252 --> 00:15:20,674
She's all wrong.

157
00:15:21,254 --> 00:15:23,507
Why don't you describe her to me?

158
00:15:24,632 --> 00:15:25,679
This doll's dead,

159
00:15:27,593 --> 00:15:28,594
inside.

160
00:15:30,179 --> 00:15:32,932
That's what my parents used to
say about my eyes.

161
00:15:34,183 --> 00:15:35,981
They weren't my real parents.

162
00:15:37,103 --> 00:15:39,401
With each new family, they'd sit me down,

163
00:15:40,106 --> 00:15:41,699
ever so nice,

164
00:15:43,317 --> 00:15:46,366
but I knew soon enough

165
00:15:47,864 --> 00:15:49,366
that they'd hate me too.

166
00:15:51,200 --> 00:15:53,953
That must have been very painful for you.

167
00:15:55,371 --> 00:15:58,215
I scared them, all of them.

168
00:15:58,624 --> 00:16:01,878
You're not possessed, Jane.
You're just unwell.

169
00:16:03,379 --> 00:16:05,006
I just want to sleep,

170
00:16:06,466 --> 00:16:07,638
forever.

171
00:16:11,220 --> 00:16:14,690
Aren't you concerned that
Jane Harper will take her own life?

172
00:16:15,057 --> 00:16:18,061
That's why we keep her under surveillance
and medicated.

173
00:16:18,227 --> 00:16:22,573
So, why are you
working on this experiment, Harry?

174
00:16:22,732 --> 00:16:23,733
Me?

175
00:16:25,526 --> 00:16:27,073
Scientific pursuit.

176
00:16:27,862 --> 00:16:31,162
The equipment we're using is cutting edge,
engineer's dream.

177
00:16:46,923 --> 00:16:48,925
Help me!

178
00:16:50,510 --> 00:16:52,262
It's 95 over 70.

179
00:16:59,435 --> 00:17:01,108
So, how did you get into this?

180
00:17:01,687 --> 00:17:04,566
Initially my field was abnormal psychology,

181
00:17:04,690 --> 00:17:07,443
which, despite the frightening title,

182
00:17:07,610 --> 00:17:11,865
merely indicates
the study of behavior outside the norm.

183
00:17:13,157 --> 00:17:16,457
You run into a lot of charlatans,
con artists, and mental deficients,

184
00:17:16,577 --> 00:17:18,375
Brian, and I disproved them all.

185
00:17:18,621 --> 00:17:21,875
Then, there was David Q.

186
00:17:22,124 --> 00:17:23,376
Harry, lights.

187
00:17:26,629 --> 00:17:28,302
<i>Where are you, Mr. Gregor?</i>

188
00:17:32,468 --> 00:17:36,644
I think David used
the character of Mr. Gregor

189
00:17:37,139 --> 00:17:40,814
to explain the
telekinetic havoc his mind was wreaking.

190
00:17:41,269 --> 00:17:44,068
The same way
Jane is mentally sculpting Evey?

191
00:17:44,564 --> 00:17:45,736
Exactly.

192
00:17:46,983 --> 00:17:49,736
<i>Why is Mr. Gregor
doing these things, David?</i>

193
00:17:50,152 --> 00:17:54,658
<i>I don't know. Mother says he's evil.</i>

194
00:17:55,575 --> 00:17:57,168
<i>What do you think he is?</i>

195
00:17:57,910 --> 00:18:00,163
<i>He's bad. So am I!</i>

196
00:18:00,288 --> 00:18:03,337
<i>Mr. Gregor is make-believe!
Your mind is creating him.</i>

197
00:18:03,457 --> 00:18:05,505
<i>You can get rid of him. I can help you!</i>

198
00:18:18,347 --> 00:18:21,817
Mr. Gregor was
a character from a bedtime story

199
00:18:21,934 --> 00:18:23,936
David's father used to tell him.

200
00:18:24,103 --> 00:18:25,946
His parents must feel so guilty.

201
00:18:26,022 --> 00:18:28,024
What happened to David Q.?

202
00:18:28,774 --> 00:18:32,529
He was improving with my help,
but his mother,

203
00:18:32,987 --> 00:18:35,661
a religious woman, terminated the sessions.

204
00:18:36,032 --> 00:18:37,375
We lost touch.

205
00:18:37,700 --> 00:18:41,295
I've heard he's living
a relatively normal life somewhere.

206
00:18:46,751 --> 00:18:48,094
Hello, Joseph.

207
00:18:56,552 --> 00:18:57,599
Gentlemen.

208
00:18:59,889 --> 00:19:02,938
Why do I get the impression
this is about to become unpleasant?

209
00:19:05,519 --> 00:19:06,736
We have to move Jane.

210
00:19:07,730 --> 00:19:09,073
- What?
- Why?

211
00:19:09,231 --> 00:19:11,404
They've pulled
the funding for the experiment.

212
00:19:12,026 --> 00:19:14,074
Bloody cowards!

213
00:19:16,072 --> 00:19:18,074
They're dead already anyway.

214
00:19:18,908 --> 00:19:20,080
Krissi, Harry...

215
00:19:22,703 --> 00:19:25,047
You can leave the experiment
or see this through.

216
00:19:25,122 --> 00:19:27,921
Either way I'll understand.

217
00:19:29,377 --> 00:19:31,505
No, we're with you, Joseph.

218
00:19:33,881 --> 00:19:34,973
All the way.

219
00:19:38,386 --> 00:19:41,265
Cameraman, I'm not well off.

220
00:19:41,389 --> 00:19:43,232
I won't have much left for film.

221
00:19:44,850 --> 00:19:46,568
I'll use cheaper stock.

222
00:19:48,270 --> 00:19:51,274
After all, I'm starting to be a bit intrigued.

223
00:19:52,900 --> 00:19:56,245
It's for the best. Come on, let's pack.

224
00:20:31,230 --> 00:20:32,402
Do you like it?

225
00:20:37,695 --> 00:20:39,197
If it makes me better.

226
00:20:43,200 --> 00:20:44,372
Let's get...

227
00:20:46,579 --> 00:20:48,752
Yeah, one of all of us.

228
00:20:56,881 --> 00:21:00,806
Okay, should we go in? I got you.

229
00:21:37,546 --> 00:21:38,798
Just be careful.

230
00:22:32,768 --> 00:22:34,020
EMF scanner.

231
00:22:34,270 --> 00:22:38,867
And there's one in each corner
and one on the table. Five in total.

232
00:22:39,733 --> 00:22:44,330
Basically, they pick up minute changes
in electromagnetic energy fields.

233
00:22:45,781 --> 00:22:47,829
I borrowed them
from the Engineering Department.

234
00:22:48,576 --> 00:22:50,999
<i>So</i> if we can connect
Harper's mental activity,

235
00:22:51,120 --> 00:22:53,339
which is recorded on the EEG machine,

236
00:22:55,541 --> 00:22:59,262
to telekinetic events, then...

237
00:23:03,716 --> 00:23:06,720
So if Evey's made of negative energy,

238
00:23:06,844 --> 00:23:08,767
then this should help us identify...

239
00:23:08,888 --> 00:23:12,233
Very good, Brian, very good.

240
00:23:12,683 --> 00:23:14,026
- Are we ready?
- Yeah.

241
00:23:22,109 --> 00:23:23,281
Here we go.

242
00:23:26,155 --> 00:23:28,578
We just want to ask Evey some questions.

243
00:23:33,203 --> 00:23:36,457
Come on, Evey. Come out.

244
00:23:38,375 --> 00:23:39,797
Come play with us.

245
00:23:42,713 --> 00:23:44,966
One knock for yes, two for no.

246
00:23:46,884 --> 00:23:48,477
God, please, Evey.

247
00:23:52,973 --> 00:23:54,816
Why won't she speak to us?

248
00:23:56,644 --> 00:23:58,271
Damn it, Jane!

249
00:23:59,146 --> 00:24:00,864
I'm trying, Joseph.

250
00:24:06,779 --> 00:24:08,201
Try harder.

251
00:24:09,406 --> 00:24:12,330
So, how do we assess our progress?

252
00:24:13,452 --> 00:24:15,671
How do I assess our progress?

253
00:24:16,497 --> 00:24:21,048
Patience and courage.
Evey will slowly come to life.

254
00:24:21,543 --> 00:24:24,797
If we survive, we win a Nobel Prize.

255
00:24:24,880 --> 00:24:27,008
Wait, is there a chance we won't?

256
00:24:27,216 --> 00:24:29,560
- Win?
- Survive.

257
00:24:29,885 --> 00:24:31,432
There's always a chance.

